age and convent life. While the region's expanding urban economies initially valued the communities for their cheap labor supply, severe economic crises by the fourteenth century restricted women's opportunities for work. Church authorities had also grown less tolerant of religious experimentation, hailing as subversive some aspects of beguine mysticism. To Simons, however, such accusations of heresy against the beguines were largely generated from a profound anxiety about their intellectual ambitions and their claims to a chaste life outside the cloister. Under ecclesiastical and economic pressure, beguine communities dwindled in size and influence, surviving only by adopting a posture of restraint and submission to church authorities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBeguineszBenelux countriesxHistory. 0aChurch historyyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aMonasticism and religious orders for womenzBenelux countriesxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 4aReligious Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aGender Studies.  aHistory.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.  aWomen's Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package World Historyz978311041347208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220012640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812200126423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812200126/original  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041347-2  Penn Press eBook Package World History  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Packa